<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-513-406  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 513 406.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC User  July 19 1989 n111 p17(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EMAP Business and Computer Publications1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Microsoft problems affect Word 5 users.andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (products).andO;Ticker:    MSFT.andO;Product:   Microsoft Word 5.0 (Word processing software) (design andconstruction).andO;Topic:     DefectsGraphics Boards-CardsMiceOS-2Product Failures.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Microsoft problems affect Word 5 users Microsoft's Word 5 cannot operate amouse when in graphics mode under OS/2.andP;  And users who fail to install thenew mouse driver shipped with the product have also experienced corruption ofVGA screens.andM;The VGA corruption occurs as coloured blocks as users scroll through theirtext with a mouse.andP;  According to a Microsoft spokesman, &quot;The problem doesn'taffect the application, and there will be no loss of data.&quot;andM;Alan Dowzall, Microsoft's product manager for Word, said the screencorruption only occurs if users fail to load the mouse driver shipped withthe package.andP;  &quot;People [with VGA displays] must ensure that Word 5 is usedwith the mouse driver found on the Utilities disk 3,&quot; he explained.andP;  Thespokesman said the screen incompatibility also exists in Word 4.andM;Despite its shipment of 2,500 copies of the product, Microsoft maintains thatno users have reported the screen defect.andP;  However, Dowzall said users who doexperience difficulties should call the Microsoft Customer Service Departmenton (0734) 500741.andM;On the subject of the OS/2 mouse driver, Dowzall said this option will beavailable in the future, but was unable to supply a date.andO;</TEXT></DOC>